<h2>Functional Component Adapter</h2>
<p>
    The Functional Component Adapter allows writing functional-style components that map to class-based Web Components.
</p>

<section class="section-card">
    <h3 id="status">Status</h3>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
        <strong>POC:</strong> A first generator exists — it lowers a <code>&lt;component&gt;</code> definition to a
        functional component (a function returning JSX) plus a Custom Element wrapper that mounts it. It is one of the
        forms served by <a href="/backlog/081-module-as-a-service-provider/">Module-as-a-Service (#081)</a>; reactivity
        (hooks/effects) is not yet implemented. Try it in the
        <a href="/demos/maas-consumer-demo.html">Module-as-a-Service Consumer</a> demo.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="section-card">
    <h3 id="poc-shape">POC shape &amp; the import-map seam</h3>
    <p>
        The current generator emits a function returning the template as JSX (via the shared <code>htmlToJsx</code>
        transform, so it mirrors the other adapter forms) plus a thin element wrapper. Unlike the class form, the
        output is <strong>not self-contained</strong> — it imports the jsx runtime via a <em>bare specifier</em>
        (<code>@webeverything/jsx-runtime</code>). A consumer therefore resolves it with an
        <strong>import map</strong> — the canonical native-platform answer:
    </p>
    {% highlight "html" %}
&lt;script type="importmap"&gt;
  { "imports": { "@webeverything/jsx-runtime": "/blocks/renderers/jsx/index.ts" } }
&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;script type="module"&gt;
  await import('/_maas/user-card.js?form=functional'); // self-registers &lt;user-card&gt;
&lt;/script&gt;
    {% endhighlight %}
</section>

<section class="section-card">
    <h3 id="concept">Concept</h3>
    <p>
        Write components as simple functions while the adapter generates class-based Custom Elements under the hood:
    </p>

    {% highlight "typescript" %}
// Functional style
const Counter = (props) => {
    const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

    return html`
        <button @click=${() => setCount(count + 1)}>
            Count: ${count}
        </button>
    `;
};

// Compiles to class-based Custom Element
class CounterElement extends HTMLElement {
    // Generated implementation...
}
customElements.define('counter-element', CounterElement);
    {% endhighlight %}
</section>

